1
00:01:30,772 --> 00:01:33,707
I ask you now to pronounce judgment...

2
00:01:33,875 --> 00:01:35,399
...on those accused.

3
00:01:37,879 --> 00:01:39,176
On this...

4
00:01:39,347 --> 00:01:43,511
This mindless aberration,
whose only means of expression...

5
00:01:43,684 --> 00:01:46,050
...are wanton violence and destruction.

6
00:01:47,321 --> 00:01:48,583
On the woman, Ursa...

7
00:01:49,056 --> 00:01:52,287
...whose perversions
and unreasoning hatred of all mankind...

8
00:01:52,794 --> 00:01:56,355
...have threatened even the children
of the planet Krypton.

9
00:01:57,565 --> 00:02:00,295
Finally, General Zod.

10
00:02:00,468 --> 00:02:02,698
Chief architect of this
intended revolution...

11
00:02:02,870 --> 00:02:07,933
...and author of this insidious plot
to establish a new order amongst us...

12
00:02:08,309 --> 00:02:11,836
...with himself as absolute ruler.

13
00:02:12,814 --> 00:02:15,248
The decision of the
council will now be heard.

14
00:02:15,416 --> 00:02:16,713
Guilty.

15
00:02:17,718 --> 00:02:18,912
- Guilty.
- Guilty.

16
00:02:20,888 --> 00:02:22,480
Guilty.

17
00:02:24,826 --> 00:02:26,726
The vote must be unanimous, Jor-El.

18
00:02:27,728 --> 00:02:30,162
It has therefore now become your decision.

19
00:02:30,331 --> 00:02:32,663
You alone will condemn us if you wish...

20
00:02:32,834 --> 00:02:35,769
...and you alone
will be held responsible by me.

21
00:02:46,347 --> 00:02:48,815
You will bow down before me, Jor-El.

22
00:02:48,983 --> 00:02:50,177
I swear it.

23
00:02:50,351 --> 00:02:55,345
No matter that it takes an eternity,
you will bow down before me!

24
00:02:55,523 --> 00:02:56,615
Both you...

25
00:02:56,891 --> 00:02:57,983
...and then one day...

26
00:02:58,159 --> 00:03:00,059
...your heirs!

27
00:03:29,457 --> 00:03:33,018
You will bow down before me!

28
00:03:34,996 --> 00:03:37,362
- Forgive me!
- I'll be back!

29
00:03:37,531 --> 00:03:38,657
Forgive me!

30
00:04:11,732 --> 00:04:16,226
Your mother Lara has sent you
three blankets, of red, yellow and blue.

31
00:04:17,672 --> 00:04:20,072
Their protection
will ensure your strength.

32
00:05:29,677 --> 00:05:33,613
It's kryptonite, Superman.
A little souvenir from the old hometown.

33
00:05:38,786 --> 00:05:43,348
You were great in your day, Superman.
But it just stands to reason...

34
00:05:43,524 --> 00:05:45,958
...when it came time
to cash in your chips...

35
00:05:46,127 --> 00:05:49,563
...this old, diseased maniac...

36
00:05:49,730 --> 00:05:51,664
...would be your banker.

37
00:05:55,102 --> 00:05:57,036
Mind over muscle.

38
00:06:30,805 --> 00:06:33,000
Why did you kiss me first?

39
00:06:34,275 --> 00:06:37,301
It... I didn't think you'd let me later.

40
00:06:37,478 --> 00:06:39,275
Stand aside, now.

41
00:08:16,443 --> 00:08:18,468
Free!

42
00:12:03,070 --> 00:12:07,006
Nice fresh melons.
Nice fresh melons. Get them fresh here.

43
00:12:07,174 --> 00:12:10,041
Good for the cooking, huh?
Look at this, the best.

44
00:12:11,812 --> 00:12:14,337
"Lex Luthor's scheme bombs.
Superman saves nation.

45
00:12:14,515 --> 00:12:17,951
Master criminal draws harsh sentence.
Exclusive story by Lois Lane.

46
00:12:18,118 --> 00:12:20,245
Photographs by James Olsen."

47
00:12:20,421 --> 00:12:23,618
Luthor, you never looked lovelier.

48
00:12:23,791 --> 00:12:24,951
Lois, terrific job.

49
00:12:25,125 --> 00:12:27,093
- Thanks, chief.
- Great story, really great.

50
00:12:27,261 --> 00:12:29,456
Hey, good morning, chief. You're late.

51
00:12:29,630 --> 00:12:32,531
Yeah, Miss Lane, that's a great story.
One of the best.

52
00:12:32,699 --> 00:12:37,033
Well, Jimmy, usually a picture isn't worth
a thousand words when I write the story...

53
00:12:37,204 --> 00:12:39,035
...but in this case, congratulations.

54
00:12:39,206 --> 00:12:40,571
- Yeah, thanks a lot.
- Yeah.

55
00:12:41,642 --> 00:12:45,078
There's Mr. Kent. Bet he wishes
he'd been around when it all happened.

56
00:12:45,245 --> 00:12:47,770
Clark, he's never around
when Superman appears.

57
00:12:47,948 --> 00:12:49,438
Poor guy.

58
00:12:58,625 --> 00:13:00,252
- You got a page in the front?
- Yeah.

59
00:13:03,363 --> 00:13:05,695
Miss Lane got the best story.

60
00:13:13,073 --> 00:13:15,007
Good morning, Lois.

61
00:13:16,376 --> 00:13:17,673
Hi.

62
00:13:55,148 --> 00:13:57,446
Lane, Kent, get in here!

63
00:13:57,618 --> 00:13:59,449
Now, see, Jimmy, you got me in trouble.

64
00:13:59,620 --> 00:14:02,783
- We were talking.
- So long. A big mistake.

65
00:14:03,624 --> 00:14:05,956
Next time, don't do that to me.

66
00:14:06,293 --> 00:14:09,922
- Good morning, Lois. How are you today?
- Oh, I'm just super. Thanks.

67
00:14:10,097 --> 00:14:11,758
- Good morning, Mr. White.
- I'm super.

68
00:14:11,932 --> 00:14:15,299
- Yeah, morning. You're late, Kent.
- I know. I'm sorry, Mr. White.

69
00:14:15,469 --> 00:14:17,733
- I got stuck in traffic.
- Oh, that's a new one.

70
00:14:17,905 --> 00:14:19,668
- Excuse me?
- I mean, as opposed to:

71
00:14:19,840 --> 00:14:23,298
"I was stuck in a phone booth" or
"I got locked into the men's bathroom."

72
00:14:23,477 --> 00:14:26,105
Lois, what are you talking about?
I'm sorry I was late.

73
00:14:26,280 --> 00:14:29,044
If you two wanna bicker,
I have just the assignment for you.

74
00:14:29,216 --> 00:14:33,209
You're gonna pose as a honeymoon couple
to get an exposé on the newlywed racket.

75
00:14:33,387 --> 00:14:37,084
Some of those hotels are bilking those
poor kids for every cent they can get.

76
00:14:37,257 --> 00:14:40,488
Real human-interest stuff.
Make your Aunt Hattie cry her eyes out.

77
00:14:40,761 --> 00:14:43,787
- Newlyweds?
- That is a great idea, Mr. White.

78
00:14:43,964 --> 00:14:47,593
- I'm sorry, but I'm in the middle of a series...
- I mean, it wouldn't take long.

79
00:14:47,768 --> 00:14:52,262
We could just fly right up there
and zoom back down again.

80
00:14:52,439 --> 00:14:54,703
No, Superman?

81
00:14:54,875 --> 00:14:58,072
Yeah. If he'd give you two a ride,
maybe we could save a couple bucks.

82
00:14:58,345 --> 00:15:00,711
I gotta see young Olsen.
Six lousy photographs...

83
00:15:00,881 --> 00:15:05,318
- ...and that kid's hitting me up for a raise.
- Excuse me. Mr. White? Could we talk?

84
00:15:05,485 --> 00:15:07,009
Darn.

85
00:15:07,955 --> 00:15:10,856
You look like the cat who swallowed
the canary this morning.

86
00:15:11,024 --> 00:15:14,858
A canary? No, actually I was
thinking of something bigger...

87
00:15:15,028 --> 00:15:17,997
...something that flies,
something more in blue.

88
00:15:18,465 --> 00:15:20,433
Lois, as usual, I'm totally in the dark...

89
00:15:20,601 --> 00:15:23,832
Let me just turn on
the lights for you then.

90
00:15:25,739 --> 00:15:27,502
Get the picture?

91
00:15:29,409 --> 00:15:33,004
I didn't put this together until
this morning. Which is really strange...

92
00:15:33,180 --> 00:15:36,479
...because a good reporter isn't
supposed to let anything slip by her.

93
00:15:36,650 --> 00:15:39,084
Well, that's very amusing. Yes.

94
00:15:39,252 --> 00:15:40,719
- Excuse me.
- Amusing?

95
00:15:40,887 --> 00:15:45,290
- Yes, sirree, that's... That's very amusing.
- Amusing, huh?

96
00:15:45,525 --> 00:15:49,621
Tall, broad shoulders...

97
00:15:50,030 --> 00:15:52,055
...dark hair.

98
00:15:52,232 --> 00:15:55,167
Gotta give you credit,
you really had me fooled.

99
00:15:55,335 --> 00:15:57,929
And I'm nobody's fool...

100
00:15:58,739 --> 00:16:00,468
...Superman.

101
00:16:00,941 --> 00:16:02,272
Superman?

102
00:16:02,442 --> 00:16:06,606
You mean you think I'm Superman?

103
00:16:07,247 --> 00:16:10,375
- Willing to bet my life on it.
- Lois, you know, you are priceless.

104
00:16:10,550 --> 00:16:13,542
Really. That is the single most
ridiculous thing I've ever...

105
00:16:14,955 --> 00:16:17,822
- Lois, what are you doing?
- You wouldn't let me die, Superman.

106
00:16:57,798 --> 00:17:01,461
- Oh, God.
- Help her out. Help her out.

107
00:17:01,868 --> 00:17:04,666
- Clark!
- Lois, what have you done?

108
00:17:05,072 --> 00:17:07,700
Clark, the... You're not...

109
00:17:10,310 --> 00:17:13,643
Hey, Clark, you seen Lois?

110
00:17:16,583 --> 00:17:18,380
She just stepped out for a minute.

111
00:17:35,802 --> 00:17:38,794
This is how it ends for
the greatest criminal mind of our time.

112
00:17:38,972 --> 00:17:41,236
Not with a whimper, not with a bang.

113
00:17:41,408 --> 00:17:43,933
How do they choose to reward Lex Luthor...

114
00:17:44,111 --> 00:17:46,045
...the greatest genius in this world?

115
00:17:46,213 --> 00:17:50,115
Do they give him glory or treasure?
What, matter of fact, do they give him?

116
00:17:50,283 --> 00:17:54,379
Life plus 25, Luthor. Get to work.

117
00:17:58,692 --> 00:18:01,320
Don't feel bad, Mr. Luthor.
It almost worked.

118
00:18:01,495 --> 00:18:04,328
I mean, California almost
fell down, right in the ocean.

119
00:18:04,498 --> 00:18:06,295
Millions of people was almost killed.

120
00:18:06,466 --> 00:18:09,663
If it hadn't been for that guy
Superman, that overgrown Boy Scout.

121
00:18:09,836 --> 00:18:13,067
- I want my Liberace record back tonight.
- Tonight?

122
00:18:13,240 --> 00:18:18,303
What are you gonna do with a guy like that?
He flies around so fast and everything.

123
00:18:19,312 --> 00:18:22,509
I mean, they can't even trace
that guy on that radar they got.

124
00:18:22,716 --> 00:18:25,651
Every time they try, he just flies off.

125
00:18:25,819 --> 00:18:27,184
- Where?
- North.

126
00:18:27,387 --> 00:18:29,184
Why?

127
00:18:29,356 --> 00:18:30,653
To ski?

128
00:18:30,824 --> 00:18:34,225
Otis, every man has his vulnerable point.

129
00:18:34,394 --> 00:18:37,625
Some, like you, Otis, have more than one.

130
00:18:37,798 --> 00:18:39,732
I didn't see Superman's in time.

131
00:18:39,900 --> 00:18:43,529
But now, through patience,
invention, and skill...

132
00:18:44,571 --> 00:18:47,665
...my little black box
is just about ready.

133
00:18:47,841 --> 00:18:51,072
Oh, that little black box in our cell?

134
00:18:54,080 --> 00:18:57,140
That little black box, Mr. Luthor...

135
00:18:58,685 --> 00:19:00,585
...what's it for?

136
00:19:00,754 --> 00:19:06,556
That little black box goes beyond
any normal, conventional radar.

137
00:19:06,726 --> 00:19:09,388
It tracks alpha waves.

138
00:19:11,898 --> 00:19:14,560
Alpha waves. Yeah.

139
00:19:14,734 --> 00:19:17,464
I could've said it tracked pasta e fagioli,
couldn't I?

140
00:19:17,637 --> 00:19:21,266
Oh, with garlic, Mr. Luthor. And butter.

141
00:19:21,441 --> 00:19:22,840
Boy.

142
00:19:26,012 --> 00:19:31,575
Those alpha waves will
take me north to his secret.

143
00:19:31,751 --> 00:19:36,484
And when I have his
secret, I'll have Superman.

144
00:19:39,359 --> 00:19:42,123
Slasher Fogelstein's a bed wetter.

145
00:19:46,766 --> 00:19:50,702
Slasher Fogelstein's a bed wetter.
Pass it.

146
00:19:56,176 --> 00:19:58,110
Hi, Mr. Fogelstein.

147
00:19:58,578 --> 00:20:01,103
Too fast. Can you get the speed right?

148
00:20:01,281 --> 00:20:04,216
I told you, they installed those
three weeks ago.

149
00:20:05,151 --> 00:20:06,151
Hey.

150
00:20:07,053 --> 00:20:11,251
You follow the bouncing ball for a while.
Thing's giving me a headache.

151
00:20:11,424 --> 00:20:14,518
Anyway, somebody's gotta
check up on those guys.

152
00:20:14,694 --> 00:20:17,527
Yeah, I keep on forgetting about them.

153
00:20:17,697 --> 00:20:20,461
How long they been up there, 45 days?

154
00:20:20,634 --> 00:20:23,569
The whole world's forgotten about it.

155
00:20:25,805 --> 00:20:27,966
Houston calling Artemis II.

156
00:20:28,775 --> 00:20:31,608
Houston calling Artemis II. Come in.

157
00:20:31,778 --> 00:20:34,338
Morning, Houston. Hold on, Nate.

158
00:20:34,514 --> 00:20:36,448
- Yo.
- How are things going?

159
00:20:37,217 --> 00:20:39,685
All systems normal, Houston.

160
00:20:39,853 --> 00:20:42,754
Andy is out doing the geological survey.

161
00:20:42,923 --> 00:20:45,221
More rocks. Nice.

162
00:20:45,392 --> 00:20:48,486
And cosmonaut Boris
is getting some soil samples.

163
00:20:48,662 --> 00:20:51,222
By the way, Boris and I are engaged.

164
00:20:51,731 --> 00:20:54,859
I had a feeling about you guys
when I saw your Rorschach tests.

165
00:20:55,035 --> 00:20:57,333
Just a little détente humor there, Houston.

166
00:20:57,504 --> 00:20:59,495
Surface conditions unchanged?

167
00:20:59,673 --> 00:21:02,699
Well, it's mighty
pretty out there. Mighty...

168
00:21:04,844 --> 00:21:06,903
- ...pretty.
- Mighty pretty.

169
00:21:07,113 --> 00:21:09,240
Right.

170
00:21:09,616 --> 00:21:11,481
Look, Nate?

171
00:21:11,651 --> 00:21:13,243
Nate, wake up, will you?

172
00:21:13,420 --> 00:21:15,980
That's it. I'm dreaming.

173
00:21:16,156 --> 00:21:18,420
Artemis, come in.

174
00:21:18,625 --> 00:21:22,686
Well, Houston, we seem to have
an unidentified flying object.

175
00:21:22,862 --> 00:21:24,261
Unidentified?

176
00:21:24,931 --> 00:21:27,559
- What does it look like?
- Well...

177
00:21:27,734 --> 00:21:30,430
...a lot like a girl.

178
00:21:51,758 --> 00:21:53,555
You.

179
00:21:54,294 --> 00:21:57,786
- What kind of a creature are you?
- Just a man.

180
00:21:58,565 --> 00:22:00,658
A man?

181
00:22:57,424 --> 00:23:00,154
What a fragile sort of life form this is.

182
00:23:25,518 --> 00:23:28,180
Houston, come in. Come in, Houston.

183
00:23:36,696 --> 00:23:38,095
Come in, Houston. Come in.

184
00:23:38,264 --> 00:23:39,891
Attempting manual liftoff.

185
00:23:40,100 --> 00:23:41,328
Can somebody hear me?

186
00:23:41,801 --> 00:23:43,632
Houston!

187
00:23:44,637 --> 00:23:45,763
Come on.

188
00:23:48,641 --> 00:23:50,438
Come on, Houston!

189
00:23:51,311 --> 00:23:53,745
Oh, no. No!

190
00:23:54,280 --> 00:23:56,145
Somebody help me!

191
00:24:02,722 --> 00:24:05,714
- Artemis, Houston calling. Come in.
- What's going on?

192
00:24:05,892 --> 00:24:09,328
- I don't know. We've lost contact.
- So?

193
00:24:09,496 --> 00:24:11,191
Well, we really...

194
00:24:11,798 --> 00:24:13,629
Artemis, come in, please.

195
00:24:15,969 --> 00:24:19,666
All right, which one of you guys
is using the hair dryer?

196
00:24:22,008 --> 00:24:26,843
Strange. I tore those
metal fibers like paper.

197
00:24:27,013 --> 00:24:30,949
And what he did was amazing.

198
00:24:31,117 --> 00:24:35,554
- Something is happening.
- Yes, to all of us.

199
00:24:37,757 --> 00:24:41,955
The closer we come to an
atmosphere with only one sun...

200
00:24:42,128 --> 00:24:43,959
...a yellow sun...

201
00:24:44,130 --> 00:24:48,089
...the more our molecular
density gives us unlimited powers.

202
00:24:48,268 --> 00:24:50,065
They come from there.

203
00:24:50,236 --> 00:24:52,227
A place called Houston.

204
00:24:52,405 --> 00:24:54,805
Then we will go there too...

205
00:24:54,974 --> 00:24:56,908
...to rule.

206
00:24:57,377 --> 00:25:00,039
Finally, to rule.

207
00:25:10,523 --> 00:25:12,252
Three-eighty-two, out.

208
00:25:13,159 --> 00:25:15,525
Three-eighty-three, out.

209
00:25:16,296 --> 00:25:18,560
Three-eighty-four, out.

210
00:25:19,532 --> 00:25:21,830
Three-eighty-five, out.

211
00:25:25,205 --> 00:25:27,537
Lights out, Luthor.

212
00:25:28,107 --> 00:25:30,337
I said, lights out.

213
00:25:32,912 --> 00:25:36,609
You guys are about 10 seconds
away from solitary, you know that?

214
00:25:38,718 --> 00:25:40,743
I told you to...

215
00:25:56,236 --> 00:25:58,397
Freeze, freeze.

216
00:26:31,271 --> 00:26:33,171
Mr. Luthor.

217
00:26:34,507 --> 00:26:36,998
- How we gonna get over that wall?
- How'd we get in?

218
00:26:37,810 --> 00:26:40,370
- We flew in here, remember?
- That's how we'll get out.

219
00:26:40,546 --> 00:26:42,878
Oh, no, not that guy.

220
00:26:46,686 --> 00:26:48,415
Did you just go "psst"?

221
00:26:48,588 --> 00:26:51,751
I wish I had, Mr. Luthor, before we left.

222
00:26:53,393 --> 00:26:55,657
Not that "psst," that "psst."

223
00:26:59,032 --> 00:27:01,830
- Don't go "psst" when I go "psst."
- You do it.

224
00:27:05,338 --> 00:27:07,499
Go out there and find it.

225
00:27:08,207 --> 00:27:12,667
- What am I looking for?
- You'll know when you see it.

226
00:27:23,856 --> 00:27:26,552
I think I found it.

227
00:27:31,731 --> 00:27:33,596
What is it?

228
00:27:34,600 --> 00:27:37,467
It's a ladder, you dummy.

229
00:27:38,237 --> 00:27:39,670
Hi, Miss Teschmacher.

230
00:27:48,648 --> 00:27:49,808
Come on.

231
00:27:50,616 --> 00:27:54,245
Hurry up. Hurry up.

232
00:27:54,821 --> 00:27:57,051
Come on, hurry.

233
00:27:58,057 --> 00:28:00,423
Otis, hold that ladder. Hurry up.

234
00:28:00,593 --> 00:28:04,427
- Yard line, touchdown!
- Oh, what a beautiful play.

235
00:28:04,597 --> 00:28:07,327
But there's a marker downfield.
It could be against...

236
00:28:12,905 --> 00:28:13,963
- Come up.
- Come on.

237
00:28:14,140 --> 00:28:16,734
Here I come, Mr. Luthor.

238
00:28:18,511 --> 00:28:19,671
- Get off. Get off.
- Otis!

239
00:28:21,481 --> 00:28:24,177
- We're sinking!
- Get off, get off!

240
00:28:41,200 --> 00:28:43,361
Very good,
Miss Teschmacher. Very good.

241
00:28:43,536 --> 00:28:46,232
- What am I doing here? Why am I here?
- Miss Teschmacher...

242
00:28:46,406 --> 00:28:48,306
...is this a philosophy seminar?

243
00:28:48,474 --> 00:28:50,203
- No. This is a getaway.
- No.

244
00:28:50,376 --> 00:28:51,604
- Getaway.
- Right.

245
00:28:51,778 --> 00:28:54,770
It's ingenious. I don't know
where you got the inspiration from.

246
00:28:54,947 --> 00:28:56,676
I got it from you, Lex.

247
00:28:57,617 --> 00:28:59,551
